<Layout title="Napa Valley Wine Region" description="A guide to Napa Valley — California's premier wine region and the birthplace of world-class American Cabernet Sauvignon.">
  <section class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-6 py-20">
    <p class="text-amber-600 font-medium tracking-wider uppercase text-sm mb-3">Wine Regions</p>
    <h1 class="font-display text-4xl md:text-5xl font-bold text-stone-900 mb-6">Napa Valley: Where California Dreams in Cabernet</h1>
    <p class="text-stone-500 text-sm mb-8">By Roberto Carli, CMS · 11 min read</p>

    <div class="prose prose-stone max-w-none">
      <p class="text-lg text-stone-600 leading-relaxed">Napa Valley is the most celebrated wine region in the Americas. Just 30 miles long and 5 miles wide, this narrow valley north of San Francisco produces Cabernet Sauvignon that rivals — and often surpasses — the great estates of Bordeaux. Its story is one of ambition, innovation, and a 1976 blind tasting that changed the wine world forever.</p>

      <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold text-stone-900 mt-10">The Judgment of Paris</h2>
      <p>In 1976, British wine merchant Steven Spurrier organized a blind tasting in Paris pitting top California wines against French classics. The California wines won in both categories: the 1973 Stag's Leap Wine Cellars S.L.V. Cabernet Sauvignon beat four classified-growth Bordeaux, and the 1973 Chateau Montelena Chardonnay bested four white Burgundies. The "Judgment of Paris" shattered the assumption that great wine could only come from Europe and put Napa on the global map overnight.</p>

      <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold text-stone-900 mt-10">The Sub-AVAs</h2>
      <p>Napa Valley contains 16 sub-American Viticultural Areas (AVAs), each with distinct characteristics:</p>

      <h3 class="font-display text-xl font-bold text-stone-900 mt-6">Valley Floor</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Oakville</strong> — The epicenter. Home to legendary Cabernets from Opus One, Robert Mondavi, Screaming Eagle, and Harlan Estate. Deep, rich, structured wines with remarkable aging potential.</li>
        <li><strong>Rutherford</strong> — Known for "Rutherford Dust" — a distinctive earthy, mineral character in its Cabernets. Caymus, Inglenook, and Beaulieu Vineyard are benchmarks.</li>
        <li><strong>Stags Leap District</strong> — Produces Cabernets with unusual elegance and silky tannins. Where the Judgment of Paris winner was born.</li>
        <li><strong>Yountville</strong> — Slightly cooler, producing rich but balanced Cabernet. Also the culinary capital of Napa (home to The French Laundry).</li>
      </ul>

      <h3 class="font-display text-xl font-bold text-stone-900 mt-6">Mountain AVAs</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Howell Mountain</strong> — Above the fog line. Intense, tannic, age-worthy Cabernets with a mountain minerality. Dunn Vineyards is the icon.</li>
        <li><strong>Spring Mountain District</strong> — Western slopes above St. Helena. Elegant, structured wines from vineyards carved into the hillside.</li>
        <li><strong>Diamond Mountain District</strong> — Volcanic soils, compact berries, and bold, concentrated wines.</li>
        <li><strong>Mount Veeder</strong> — The highest and coolest of Napa's mountain AVAs. Rustic, tannic, wildly aromatic Cabernets.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3 class="font-display text-xl font-bold text-stone-900 mt-6">Cooler Climate Areas</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Carneros</strong> — At the southern end, cooled by San Pablo Bay breezes. Primarily Chardonnay and Pinot Noir — and excellent sparkling wine (Domaine Carneros, Artesa).</li>
        <li><strong>Calistoga</strong> — At the hot northern end, producing powerful, ripe Cabernets and excellent Petite Sirah.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold text-stone-900 mt-10">Beyond Cabernet</h2>
      <p>While Cabernet Sauvignon is king, Napa produces outstanding wines from other varieties:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Chardonnay</strong> — Rich, oak-influenced styles from Carneros and cooler valley floor sites</li>
        <li><strong>Merlot</strong> — Yes, seriously. Duckhorn's Three Palms Vineyard Merlot proves the variety thrives here</li>
        <li><strong>Sauvignon Blanc</strong> — "Fumé Blanc" style, often with oak influence. Cakebread and Robert Mondavi set the standard</li>
        <li><strong>Zinfandel</strong> — Old vine plantings on Howell Mountain and Calistoga produce powerful, spicy Zins</li>
        <li><strong>Cabernet Franc</strong> — Gaining recognition as a standalone variety, especially from hillside sites</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold text-stone-900 mt-10">The Price Question</h2>
      <p>Napa Valley Cabernet Sauvignon is expensive. The top "cult" wines (Screaming Eagle, Harlan, Scarecrow) sell for $500–$1,000+ per bottle and are allocated years in advance. Even mid-tier Napa Cab typically runs $50–$150.</p>
      <p>For value, look to:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Napa Valley appellation</strong> (not sub-AVA) Cabernets — $25–$50 from producers like Textbook, The Prisoner Wine Company, and Charles Krug</li>
        <li><strong>Second labels</strong> from prestigious estates — The Mascot (from the families behind Harlan, Bond, and Promontory), Decoy (by Duckhorn)</li>
        <li><strong>Non-Cabernet varieties</strong> — Napa Sauvignon Blanc and Merlot often deliver better QPR (quality-to-price ratio)</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold text-stone-900 mt-10">Visiting Napa</h2>
      <p>As a sommelier based just an hour south in Redwood City, I'm in Napa regularly. A few tips for visitors: book tastings in advance (many wineries are appointment-only), start early in the day (your palate fatigues quickly), spit at most stops (you'll taste better and enjoy more), and don't skip the small, off-highway producers — they're often making the most interesting wines.</p>
      <p>If you'd like a curated Napa experience, my <a href="/services/private-tastings" class="text-amber-700 hover:text-amber-800">Private Tastings</a> service can extend to winery visits with insider access.</p>
